              <h3 class="font-heading text-white text-lg font-semibold mb-2">Gallatin Pike Concept Turnover: New Cooking, Old Equipment</h3>
              <p class="text-[#D4D4D4]">Madison's mid-century commercial strips along Gallatin Pike are experiencing a wave of revitalization. Authentic Latin American concepts, heavy soul food kitchens, and high-heat international restaurants move into spaces formerly occupied by sandwich shops or light-cooking operations. The problem: the existing exhaust system was sized for the previous concept. A kitchen that now runs three high-heat woks will instantly overwhelm an undersized fan motor, coat the ductwork in baked-on carbon, and fail the next Metro Nashville inspection. DDAN evaluates these mismatched systems and performs the <a href="/repair/madison-tn/" class="text-[#FF5E15] hover:underline">motor upgrades, access panel installations, and hinge kit retrofits</a> required to bring them up to code for the new cooking volume.</p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h3 class="font-heading text-white text-lg font-semibold mb-2">Diverse Cuisine Creates Diverse Grease Challenges</h3>
              <p class="text-[#D4D4D4]">No other Nashville neighborhood produces the range of exhaust system contamination that Madison does. Woks and open-flame grills create hardened carbon scale that requires specialized scraping. Heavy soul food fryers generate thick, sticky grease deposits. Standard surface cleaning cannot handle the variety — each concept needs a different approach. DDAN's technicians are trained to identify the specific buildup type and apply the right combination of chemical treatment and mechanical scraping to return every system to bare metal.</p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h3 class="font-heading text-white text-lg font-semibold mb-2">Rivergate Overlap: New Roofs, Old Problems</h3>
              <p class="text-[#D4D4D4]">The Rivergate Mall outparcels and newer constructions along the Gallatin Pike/Rivergate corridor feature TPO roofing membranes that grease runoff will permanently stain and degrade. Meanwhile, the aging EPDM and built-up roofing on older Madison strips is even more vulnerable to grease saturation. Both roof types need proper containment — and Metro Nashville's F.O.G. enforcement through Metro Water Services makes rooftop compliance non-optional regardless of building age.</p>
            </div>
